SIMPLE: miss
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Miss
<hw>Miss</hw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Misses</plw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧s"s⟦ecr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Contr. fr.
<ets>mistress</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A title of courtesy
prefixed to the name of a girl or a woman who has not been married. See
<er>Mistress</er>, 5.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ There is diversity of usage in the application of this
title to two or more persons of the same name. We may write either
<xex>the Miss Browns</xex> or <xex>the Misses Brown</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A young unmarried woman or a girl; <as>as, she is a
<ex>miss</ex> of sixteen</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gay vanity, with smiles and kisses,⟦br⟧
Was busy 'mongst the maids and misses.</q>
<rj><qau>Cawthorn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A kept mistress. See <er>Mistress</er>, 4.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>In the game of three-card
loo, an extra hand, dealt on the table, which may be substituted for the
hand dealt to a player.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Miss
<hw>Miss</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Missed</conjf> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧st)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Missing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>missan</ets>; akin to
D. & G. <ets>missen</ets>, OHG. <ets>missan</ets>, Icel.
<ets>missa</ets>, Sw. <ets>mista</ets>, Dan. <ets>miste</ets>.
⟦root⟧100. See <er>Mis-</er>, pref.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fail of
hitting, reaching, getting, finding, seeing, hearing, etc.; <as>as, to
<ex>miss</ex> the mark one shoots at; to <ex>miss</ex> the train by
being late; to <ex>miss</ex> opportunites of getting knowledge; to
<ex>miss</ex> the point or meaning of something said.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When a man <qex>misses</qex> his great end, happiness, he will
acknowledge he judged not right.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To omit; to fail to have or to do; to get without;
to dispense with; -- now seldom applied to persons.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She would never <qex>miss</qex>, one day,⟦br⟧
A walk so fine, a sight so gay.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We cannot <qex>miss</qex> him; he does make our fire,⟦br⟧
Fetch in our wood.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To discover the absence or omission of; to feel the
want of; to mourn the loss of; to want; <as>as, to <ex>miss</ex> an
absent loved one</as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither <qex>missed</qex> we anything . . . Nothing was
<qex>missed</qex> of all that pertained unto him.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam.
xxv. 15, 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What by me thou hast lost, thou least shalt <qex>miss</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To miss stays</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Stay</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Miss
<hw>Miss</hw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
fail to hit; to fly wide; to deviate from the true direction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men observe when things hit, and not when they
<qex>miss</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Flying bullets now,⟦br⟧
To execute his rage, appear too slow;⟦br⟧
They <qex>miss</qex>, or sweep but common souls away.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fail to obtain, learn, or find; -- with
<xex>of</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Upon the least reflection, we can not <qex>miss</qex> of them.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To go wrong; to err.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Amongst the angels, a whole legion⟦br⟧
Of wicked sprites did fall from happy bliss;⟦br⟧
What wonder then if one, of women all, did <qex>miss</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be absent, deficient, or wanting.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <see>See <er>Missing</er>, <pos>a.</pos></see>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What here shall <qex>miss</qex>, our toil shall strive to
mend.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Miss
<hw>Miss</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of missing;
failure to hit, reach, find, obtain, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Loss; want; felt absence.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There will be no great <qex>miss</qex> of those which are
lost.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Mistake; error; fault.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He did without any great <qex>miss</qex> in the hardest points of
grammar.</q> <rj><qau>Ascham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Harm from mistake.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missa</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
